#Inheritance in OOP is a mechanism where a new class (subclass/child) acquires properties and methods of an existing class (superclass/parent), promoting code reusability, maintainability, and establishing an "is-a" relationship. It allows extending functionality without modifying the original base class code, reducing redundancy. 

#
Key Concepts & Terminology
Superclass/Parent: The class being inherited from.
Subclass/Child: The class that inherits from the superclass.
extends / : Keyword: Used to establish the inheritance relationship (e.g., class Dog extends Animal in Java/JS, or class Dog(Animal) in Python).
"Is-a" Relationship: A mechanism that establishes a hierarchical connection (e.g., a "Dog" is-a "Animal").
Member Access: Subclasses inherit public and protected members, but generally cannot access private members directly. 

#Types of Inheritance
Single: A subclass inherits from one superclass.
Multilevel: A derived class inherits from another derived class (chaining).
Hierarchical: Multiple subclasses inherit from a single superclass.
Multiple: A subclass inherits from more than one superclass (Supported in Python/C++, not directly in Java/C#).
Hybrid: A combination of two or more types. 

#Key Benefits
Code Reusability: Features in a parent class do not need to be rewritten in child classes.
Method Overriding: Subclasses can provide a specific implementation of a method already defined in the parent class.
Polymorphism: Enables using a subclass object through a parent class reference.
Extensibility: New functionality can be added to subclasses without changing the parent class



#Important Considerations
Tight Coupling: Changes in the parent class can inadvertently affect derived classes.
Constructor Handling: Constructors are not inherited; they must be called using super().
Diamond Problem: Ambiguity in multiple inheritance where a subclass inherits from two parents that share a common grandparent.
